item.description:
@Fear_Nuture wrote:

[quote=“Crooks, post:2, topic:434955”]Hiiiiia, Once the last record is with the ID (for example): 222222222, when you insert a new record the ID should be 222222223. But mysql reduce it inside the valid range and tries to insert the ID 222222222, therefore it produces a duplicate key entry.

Maybe its better to set it as unsigned int or a unsigned bigint.
(repairing the table might also work)

Atm it re using the ID’s of the erased rows and the duplicate key will be displayed again depending on how may rows were deleted from the table previously.[/quote]

so in the db, change it to logins to unsigned int? and what your sayin is this error will happen again if i dont fix?

item.title: Now i definitely know I didn't
item.dc:creator: @Crooks Crooks
item.description:
@Crooks wrote:

Hiiiiia, Once the last record is with the ID (for example): 222222222, when you insert a new record the ID should be 222222223. But mysql reduce it inside the valid range and tries to insert the ID 222222222, therefore it produces a duplicate key entry.

Maybe its better to set it as unsigned int or a unsigned bigint.
(repairing the table might also work)

Atm it re using the ID’s of the erased rows and the duplicate key will be displayed again depending on how may rows were deleted from the table previously.
